parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of airbags to deploy in a crash can lead to serious injuries or fatalities, as the occupants of the vehicle may not be adequately protected.
symptoms: Airbags do not deploy in a crash
even when the vehicle is traveling at a moderate to high speed
and the impact is significant enough to warrant airbag deployment.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The unintended deployment of airbags can cause unexpected and potentially dangerous situations, such as loss of control of the vehicle, accidents, or injuries.
symptoms: Airbags deploy unexpectedly
without a crash or significant impact
such as when closing a door or driving at a low speed.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Delays or difficulties in repairing or replacing recalled airbag components can leave vehicles on the road with potentially defective airbags, putting occupants at risk.
symptoms: Difficulty in scheduling repairs or obtaining replacement parts for recalled airbag components
or experiencing delays in the repair process.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Excessive oil consumption can lead to engine fires, thick smoke, and toxic emissions, posing a hazard to the driver, passengers, and surrounding vehicles.
symptoms: Vehicle consumes an excessive amount of oil
leading to thick smoke and toxic emissions; engine may seize or stall; oil level drops rapidly.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Engine stalling or failure can cause accidents, especially when driving at high speeds or in heavy traffic, and can lead to engine fires or damage.
symptoms: Engine stalls or fails without warning; vehicle may lose power or hesitate; engine warning light may illuminate.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Crankshaft or Camshaft Position Sensor Failure
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Failure of the crankshaft or camshaft position sensor can cause engine stalling, loss of power, or hesitation, leading to accidents or engine damage.
symptoms: Engine stalls or fails without warning; vehicle may lose power or hesitate; engine warning light may illuminate; crankshaft or camshaft position sensor fails.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Delayed Cranking or Engine Hard to Start
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Delayed cranking or engine hard to start can cause inconvenience, especially in hot weather, and may lead to engine damage or stalling.
symptoms: Engine takes a long time to start or is hard to start
especially in hot weather; delayed cranking.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the crankshaft and camshaft sensors can cause the engine to stall or shut off while driving, leading to a loss of power steering and braking functionality, which can increase the risk of accidents.
symptoms: The engine stalls or shuts off while driving
the vehicle loses power steering and braking functionality
the instrument panel goes blank
the engine light comes on
the vehicle is hard to start
the oil intake becomes excessive.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Excessive oil consumption can lead to engine damage, increased emissions, and decreased fuel efficiency, which can result in costly repairs and potentially cause accidents.
symptoms: The vehicle consumes more oil than normal
the oil level drops rapidly
the engine makes a ticking or knocking sound.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The throttle control issues can cause the vehicle to stall or lose power while driving, leading to a loss of control and increasing the risk of accidents.
symptoms: The throttle goes out unexpectedly
the engine is still powered on but acceleration is not possible
the vehicle stalls or loses power while driving.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the serpentine belt can cause the engine to overheat, leading to costly repairs and potentially causing accidents.
symptoms: The serpentine belt makes a squeaky sound
the belt needs to be replaced frequently.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The brake issues can cause the vehicle to lose stopping power, leading to accidents and injuries.
symptoms: The brakes squeak or make a noise
the brake pads need to be replaced frequently.
